                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-12-01">
                    <head>1 December 1847</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-12-01"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="1003"/>
                        <dateline>1847— Wednesday— 1. December—</dateline>
                        <p>Glory to Almighty God— His Will be done—</p>
                        <p>[“]He that justifieth the wicked, and he that condemneth the just, even
                            they both, are abomination to the Lord.” Proverbs. 17.15.</p>
                        <p>This quotation from scripture was repeated to me in the year 1787. by
                            Theophilus Parsons, with whom I was then a student at Law at Newbury
                            Port— In the course of my daily reading of the Scripture this morning I
                            came to it again— Fifty years have passed away since it was impressed
                            upon my Memory and committed to my heart as a precept of heavenly
                            Wisdom—</p>
                        <p>I called this morning at the Treasury Department and recommended to the
                            Secretary M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Robert J Walker Captain Charles
                            Swift of Quincy for the appointment of keeper of the light-house newly
                            constructed at Minot’s ledge on Cohassett rocks—he sent for the papers
                            by which Captain Swift had been recommended before through the agency of
                                D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> William Brazier Duggan, which papers
                            had been transmitted to the Secretary by the 5<hi rend="superscript"
                                >th</hi> auditor Stephen Pleasonton on the 23 of October last, and
                            the Secretary after looking over the recommendations immediately ordered
                            the appointment to be made— I had a long conversation of speculative
                            politics, with M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Walker and I consider
                            every word henceforth issuing from my lips as my last words and dying
                            speech.</p>
                        <p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> John Mason jun<hi rend="superscript"
                                >r</hi> and Col<hi rend="superscript">l</hi> Kearney were here— M<hi
                                rend="superscript">r</hi> Foster and M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                            Thompson of Indiana. Members elect of H.R.U.S. Card from John Taliaferro
                            of Virginia</p>
                        <p>Theodore Talbot spent the evening here—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-12-02">
                    <head>2 December 1847</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-12-02"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="1004" type="ms"/>
                        <dateline>1847. Thursday 2. Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                            1847—</dateline>
                        <p>Birth-day of my grand-daughter Mary Louisa Adams who enters this day on
                            her twentieth year.</p>
                        <p>Joseph Grinnell arrived yesterday and visited us</p>
                        <p>Robert C. Winthrop this morning</p>
                        <p>Robert C. Dyson a boy about 12 years of age brought me a note from M<hi
                                rend="superscript">rs</hi> Colvin, his aunt, soliciting my influence
                            to obtain for him the appointment of a page to the House of
                            Representatives— I desired him to say to M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                            Colvin that I should be very glad if I could contribute to his obtaining
                            the appointment of a page—but I had already recommended one and I could
                            not expect that my influence could have any weight for more than one— I
                            would name him to the Doorkeeper; but he would do well to apply for the
                            influence of members possessing more than mine.</p>
                        <p>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Shryock a widow solicits employment in
                            the folding room of H.R.U.S. for her Son Samuel Shryock 16 years old who
                            has lost his father.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-12-03">
                    <head>3 December 1847</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-12-03"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="1005" type="ms"/>
                        <dateline>1847— Friday 3. Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 1847.</dateline>
                        <p>Awake and heard the Clock strike 2. Then slept till the Clock struck
                            5—lay awake till 7. then I rose with crippled hands</p>
                        <lg>
                            <l>What is an Album? tis a record fair</l>
                            <l>of thoughts inspir’d by Friendship and by Love— </l>
                            <l>Where each contributor supplies his share</l>
                            <l>of <unclear><hi rend="strikethrough">trash</hi></unclear> soul from
                                earth, or <hi rend="strikethrough">wisdom</hi>
                                <unclear>. . .</unclear> from heaven above</l>
                            <l>But as in lots unequal soul is given</l>
                            <l><unclear>And by</unclear> compound issues from the whole</l>
                            <l>And here a thought comes flushing bright from heaven</l>
                            <l>And there a dunciad from an earth born soul—</l>
                        </lg>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-12-04">
